 to address international terrorism can we make sense of the reasoning behind the actions of George W. Bush, Barack Obama, and Donald Trump, all of whom inherited, continued, and expanded on Clinton-era policies and practices. Drawing on official documents and on interviews with key players, he reveals the evolution of counterterrorism strategy throughout the Clinton administration, as well as the ramifications that it has today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001. 0aTerrorismxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aTerrorismzUnited StatesxPrevention. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311078355140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637748640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626377486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626377486/original  a978-3-11-078355-1  Lynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK